Review rubric:
- Used /workspace/ishandhanani-dotfiles/agents/skills/cursor-code-review/SKILL.md.
- Focus: structural maintainability, abstraction boundaries, duplicated bridge logic, and misleading metadata contracts.

Findings:
1. Medium: initial bridge wiring duplicated thin trainer-loop materialization helpers in both vLLM and SGLang runtime modules.
   That would make the trainer-loop publication boundary drift as the real trainer path lands.
   Resolution: moved the generic publication call into refit_mx_runtime_common.materialize_trainer_loop_publication; vLLM/SGLang keep only runtime-specific source ownership and artifact wiring.

2. Medium: loop-published ownerships carried trainer_loop_update_source but still left the generic trainer_update_source value from the underlying single-step publisher.
   That made the metadata contract ambiguous for downstream control-plane consumers.
   Resolution: _annotate_trainer_loop_publication now overwrites trainer_update_source to torch.optim.SGD-trainer-loop-smoke, and tests/artifact assertions cover it.

Non-blockers checked:
- No changed file crosses 1000 lines. Largest changed files after the fix are refit_sglang_mx_runtime.py at 834 lines and refit_vllm_mx_runtime.py at 792 lines.
- The target/source model-version contract is centralized through trainer_loop_runtime_model_version, so source endpoints and receiver requests use the same step-specific model version.
- The docs keep the claim boundary explicit: CPU/control-plane runtime bridge metadata evidence only, not a new GPU runtime rerun and not real distributed RL/FSDP trainer ownership.

